1 STATE OF OKLAHOMA
2 2nd Session of the 60th Legislature (2026)
3 COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE
FOR
4 SENATE BILL 1325 By: Coleman
5
6
7 COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE
8 An Act relating to the Protection from Domestic Abuse
Act; amending 22 O.S. 2021, Section 60.17, which
9 relates to victim protective orders; updating
statutory language; requiring defendants charged with
10 certain domestic violence offenses to use a Global
Positioning System (GPS) device when released on
11 bond; requiring defendant to pay certain costs;
requiring monitoring by the Department of
12 Corrections; authorizing removal under certain
circumstance; authorizing certain location monitoring
13 by victim; and providing an effective date.
14
15
16 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
17 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 22 O.S. 2021, Section 60.17, is
18 amended to read as follows:
19 Section 60.17. A. The court shall consider the safety of any
20 and all alleged victims of domestic violence, stalking, harassment,
21 sexual assault, or forcible sodomy where the defendant is alleged to
22 have violated a protective order, committed domestic assault and
23 battery, stalked, sexually assaulted, or forcibly sodomized the
24 alleged victim or victims prior to the release of the alleged
Req. No. 3655 Page 1

1 defe ndant from custody on bond. The court, after consideration and
2 to ensure the safety of the alleged victim or victims, may issue an
3 emergency protective order pursuant to the Protection from Domestic
4 Abuse Act. The court may also issue to the alleged victim or
5 victims an order restraining the alleged defendant from any activity
6 or action from which they he or she may be restrained under the
7 Protection from Domestic Abuse Act. The court shall not consider a
8 “no contact order as condition of bond” as a factor when determining
9 whether the petitioner is eligible for relief. The protective order
10 shall remain in effect until either a plea has been accepted,
11 sentencing has occurred in the case, the case has been dismissed, or
12 until further order of the court dismissing the protective order.
13 In conjunction with any protective order or restraining order
14 authorized by this section, the court may order the defendant to use
15 an active, real-time, twenty-four-hour Global Positioning System
16 (GPS) monitoring device for such term as the court deems
17 appropriate. Upon application of the victim, the court may
18 authorize the victim to monitor the location of the defendant. Such
19 monitoring by the victim shall be limited to the ability of the
20 victim to make computer or cellular inquiries to determine if the
21 defendant is within a specified distance of locations, excluding the
22 residence or workplace of the defendant, or to receive a computer-
23 or a cellular-generated signal if the defendant comes within a
24 specified distance of the victim. The court shall conduct an annual
Req. No. 3655 Page 2

1 revi ew of the monitoring order to determine if such order to monitor
2 the location of the defendant is still necessary. Before the court
3 orders the use of a GPS device, the court shall find that the
4 defendant has a history that demonstrates an intent to commit
5 violence against the victim, including, but not limited to, prior
6 conviction for an offense under the Protection from Domestic Abuse
7 Act or any other violent offense, or any other evidence that shows
8 by a preponderance of the evidence that the defendant is likely to
9 commit violence against the victim. The court may further order the
10 defendant to pay costs and expenses related to the GPS device and
11 monitoring.
12 B. 1. Any defendant charged with domestic abuse by
13 strangulation, domestic abuse with a dangerous or deadly weapon, or
14 domestic abuse after a previous adjudication for domestic abuse
15 shall not be released on bail without a GPS monitoring device
16 attached to the defendant. The cost of the monitoring device shall
17 be paid by the defendant at his or her own expense until the
18 conclusion of the criminal case. The Department of Corrections
19 shall monitor such GPS monitoring device and the defendant until the
20 conclusion of the case, and the defendant shall pay a supervision
21 fee as provided for other persons subject to supervision by the
22 Department. At the conclusion of the case, the court shall order
23 the removal of the GPS monitoring device if the defendant is
24 acquitted, is to be incarcerated, or the case is dismissed.
Req. No. 3655 Page 3

1 2. Upon application of the victim, the court may authorize the
2 victim to monitor the location of the defendant by receiving a
3 computer- or cellular-generated signal if the defendant comes within
4 a specified distance of the victim.
5 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
